<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,1300,2009]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,223,1300,1325]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Note.</emphasis>
According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Tucker" box="[389,679,1300,1325]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Tucker, J. K. &amp; Tenorio, M. J. (2009) Systematic classification of recent and fossil conoidean gastropods. ConchBooks, Hackenheim, 296 pp." type="book" year="2009">Tucker &amp; Tenorio (2009)</bibRefCitation>
, the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="da Motta, 1991" authorityName="da Motta" authorityYear="1991" box="[810,1120,1300,1325]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Kalloconus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[810,937,1300,1325]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Kalloconus</emphasis>
da 
<bibRefCitation author="Motta" box="[981,1120,1300,1324]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="da Motta, A. J. (1991) A systematic classification of the gastropod family Conidae at the generic level. La Conchiglia, Roma, 48 pp." type="book" year="1991">Motta, 1991</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
is characterised by large to very large and obconic shells, with a broad, rounded shoulder. The spire whorls can be smooth, striate with the sculpture disappearing on later whorls, or persisting as crowded, weak spirals. The protoconch is multispiral. The subsutural flexure is moderately deep to deep in larger specimens, and shallower in smaller specimens. The shell is ornamented with spots and dashes in spiral rows. In their molecular phylogeny, 
<bibRefCitation box="[1038,1308,1444,1469]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Puillandre, N., Duda, T. F., Meyer, C., Olivera, B. M. &amp; Bouchet, P. (2014 a) One, four or 100 genera? A new classification of the cone snails. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 8, 1 - 23." type="journal article">
Puillandre 
<emphasis box="[1159,1208,1444,1469]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">et al</emphasis>
. (2014a)
</bibRefCitation>
recognised this group as being monophyletic, albeit at subgeneric level, and a sister group to 
<taxonomicName authority="Monterosato, 1923" authorityName="Monterosato" authorityYear="1923" box="[1061,1192,1481,1504]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Lautoconus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1061,1192,1481,1504]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Lautoconus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Both of these genera today have a West African and European distribution. However, whereas 
<bibRefCitation author="Tucker" box="[987,1273,1516,1541]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Tucker, J. K. &amp; Tenorio, M. J. (2009) Systematic classification of recent and fossil conoidean gastropods. ConchBooks, Hackenheim, 296 pp." type="book" year="2009">Tucker &amp; Tenorio (2009)</bibRefCitation>
included only two extant species within the genus, 
<taxonomicName box="[572,693,1552,1577]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pulcher">
<emphasis box="[572,693,1552,1577]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">C. pulcher</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
[
<bibRefCitation author="Lightfoot" box="[707,891,1552,1577]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Lightfoot, J. (1786) [Descriptions of species] In: A Catalogue of the Portland Museum, lately the property of the Dowager Duchess of Portland, deceased, which will be sold at auction, by Mr. Skinner &amp; Co. London. Privately published, London, VIII + 194 pp." type="book" year="1786">Lightfoot, 1786</bibRefCitation>
] and 
<taxonomicName authority="Roding, 1798" authorityName="Roding" authorityYear="1798" box="[955,1267,1552,1577]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="byssinus">
<emphasis box="[955,1083,1552,1577]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">C. byssinus</emphasis>
(RÃ¶ding, 1798)
</taxonomicName>
, the molecular phylogeny by 
<bibRefCitation box="[322,610,1588,1613]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Puillandre, N., Duda, T. F., Meyer, C., Olivera, B. M. &amp; Bouchet, P. (2014 a) One, four or 100 genera? A new classification of the cone snails. Journal of Molluscan Studies, 8, 1 - 23." type="journal article">
Puillandre 
<emphasis box="[449,511,1588,1613]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">et al.</emphasis>
(2014a)
</bibRefCitation>
included six further species: 
<taxonomicName authority="Kiener, 1850" authorityName="Kiener" authorityYear="1850" box="[965,1274,1588,1613]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="ateralbus">
<emphasis box="[965,1109,1588,1613]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">C. ateralbus</emphasis>
Kiener, 1850
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Linnaeus, 1758" authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1758" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="genuanus">
<emphasis box="[1291,1436,1589,1612]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">C. genuanus</emphasis>
Linnaeus, 1758
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Reeve, 1844" authorityName="Reeve" authorityYear="1844" box="[336,622,1624,1649]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="trochulus">
<emphasis box="[336,474,1624,1649]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">C. trochulus</emphasis>
Reeve, 1844
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Hwass in Bruguiere, 1792" authorityName="Hwass in Bruguiere" authorityYear="1792" box="[633,1073,1624,1649]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="venulatus">
<emphasis box="[633,773,1624,1649]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">C. venulatus</emphasis>
Hwass in 
<bibRefCitation author="Bruguiere" box="[888,1073,1624,1649]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Bruguiere, M. (1792) Encyclopedie methodique. Histoire naturale des Vers. Tome Ier. Impensis Panckoucke, Paris, 345 - 752 pp." type="book chapter" year="1792">BruguiÃ¨re, 1792</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName authority="Afonso &amp; Tenorio, 2004" authorityName="Afonso &amp; Tenorio" authorityYear="2004" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="atlanticoselvagem">
<emphasis box="[1083,1319,1624,1649]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">C. atlanticoselvagem</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Afonso" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Afonso, C. M. L. &amp; Tenorio, M. J. (2004) Description of a new offshore species of Conus from the Cape Verde Archipelago (Gastropoda, Conidae). La Conchiglia: International Shell Magazine, 36 (310), 33 - 40." type="journal article" year="2004">Afonso &amp; Tenorio, 2004</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Monteiro, Tenorio &amp; Poppe, 2004" authorityName="Monteiro, Tenorio &amp; Poppe" authorityYear="2004" box="[365,993,1660,1685]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Conus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pseudonivifer">
<emphasis box="[365,596,1660,1685]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Conus pseudonivifer</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Monteiro" box="[605,993,1660,1685]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Monteiro, A., Tenorio, M. J., Poppe, G. T. (2004) The family Conidae: The West African and Mediterranean species of Conus. A Conchological Iconography. ConchBooks, Hackenheim, 102 pp." type="book" year="2004">Monteiro, Tenorio &amp; Poppe, 2004</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
. Although the molecular phylogenetics have led to a wider generic concept, the generic description of the shell remains unchanged.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="53.[151,1437,1300,2009]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">
Based on Paratethyan material here reviewed, we can add that 
<taxonomicName authority="da Motta, 1991" authorityName="da Motta" authorityYear="1991" box="[895,1023,1732,1757]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Kalloconus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[895,1023,1732,1757]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Kalloconus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species are small to very large, squat to moderately elongate. The spire is always low to very low; spire whorls are convex and usually smooth except for occasional striae on early spire whorls. The proto-Mediterranean 
<taxonomicName authority="Lamarck, 1810" authorityName="Lamarck" authorityYear="1810" box="[908,1384,1804,1829]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Kalloconus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="betulinoides">
<emphasis box="[908,1183,1804,1829]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Kalloconus betulinoides</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Lamarck" box="[1201,1376,1804,1829]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Lamarck, J. B. P. A. de (1810) Descriptions des coquilles fossiles des environs de Paris. Annales du Museum National d'Histoire Naturelle, 15, 422 - 44." type="journal article" year="1810">Lamarck, 1810</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
is a fossil species with striate spire whorls like the extant type species 
<taxonomicName authority="da Motta, 1991" authorityName="da Motta" authorityYear="1991" box="[909,1130,1840,1865]" class="Gastropoda" family="Conidae" genus="Kalloconus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neogastropoda" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pulcher">
<emphasis box="[909,1130,1840,1865]" italics="true" pageId="53" pageNumber="54">Kalloconus pulcher</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
([
<bibRefCitation author="Lightfoot" box="[1153,1348,1840,1865]" pageId="53" pageNumber="54" refString="Lightfoot, J. (1786) [Descriptions of species] In: A Catalogue of the Portland Museum, lately the property of the Dowager Duchess of Portland, deceased, which will be sold at auction, by Mr. Skinner &amp; Co. London. Privately published, London, VIII + 194 pp." type="book" year="1786">Lightfoot], 1786</bibRefCitation>
). Spiral sculpture on last whorl very reduced. The depth of the subsutural flexures in all our fossil species is highly variable, ranging from very shallow to deep; they are usually moderately curved and moderately asymmetrical. The last whorl is of medium to wide width. As with the living species, the colour pattern in most of the fossil representatives is also composed of spiral rows of spots and dashes; only few species develop continuous spirals.
</paragraph>
